{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/blog/css-selection-styles/","webpackCompilationHash":"df51a02b1c68429c5c32","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"James Ford","author":"James Ford"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"d95d9c8c-ea85-530a-8ccc-0ff042fb2e8d","html":"<p>Did you know you could customize the selection colours of html pages with CSS?  I didn't - until now.  Turns out, there's a <a href=\"http://www.w3.org/TR/css3-selectors/#UIfragments\" title=\"Open link in a new window\">CSS3 pseudo-element called ::selection</a>.  Naturally, this isn't yet a technique supported by browsers like Internet Explorer, but it is supported in [albeit with different syntax] by Firefox and Safari.  Interesting, eh?  Check an article on <a href=\"http://www.quirksmode.org/css/selection.html\" title=\"Open link in a new window\">CSS Selection Styles from Quirksmode</a>, and have a look at some of the creative effects you can get with it <a href=\"http://metaatem.net/selcolor.php\" title=\"Open link in a new window\">here</a>.</p>","frontmatter":{"title":"CSS Selection Styles?","date":"February 24, 2008","tags":["css"],"url":null,"image":null,"description":null,"image_credit":null}}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"prev":{"frontmatter":{"path":"/blog/adobe-on-air-comes-to-london/","tags":["adobe","air","conferences"],"title":"Adobe on AIR comes to London...","date":"2008-02-23T15:59:34.000Z","description":null,"image":{"childImageSharp":{"sizes":{"base64":"data:image/jpeg;base64,","aspectRatio":1.3333333333333333,"src":"/static/5e6f52f5024c2e528703cf8a37279a24/7dae8/adobecom.jpg","srcSet":"/static/5e6f52f5024c2e528703cf8a37279a24/10bdc/adobecom.jpg 158w,\n/static/5e6f52f5024c2e528703cf8a37279a24/f4ab0/adobecom.jpg 315w,\n/static/5e6f52f5024c2e528703cf8a37279a24/7dae8/adobecom.jpg 320w","sizes":"(max-width: 320px) 100vw, 320px"}}}}},"next":{"frontmatter":{"path":"/blog/trouble-migrating-to-actionscript-3/","tags":["acti